<div class="FunctionDoc YAMLDoc" id="log-close" markdown="1">

## [function __log\.close__\(\)](#function-__logclose__) {#function-__logclose__}

Closes the current log.

__Example:__

{% highlight python %}
log.close()
{% endhighlight %}

</div>

[log.close]: #log-close
[close]: #log-close

<div class="FunctionDoc YAMLDoc" id="log-open" markdown="1">

## [function __log\.open__\(path\)](#function-__logopen__path) {#function-__logopen__path}

Opens the current log. If a log was already open, it is closed automatically.

__Example:__

{% highlight python %}
# Open a new log
log.open(u'/path/to/new/logfile.csv')
{% endhighlight %}

__Arguments:__

- `path` -- The path to the current logfile. In most cases (unless) a custom log back-end is used, this will be a filename.
	- Type: str, unicode

</div>

[log.open]: #log-open
[open]: #log-open

<div class="FunctionDoc YAMLDoc" id="log-write" markdown="1">

## [function __log\.write__\(msg, newline=True\)](#function-__logwrite__msg-newlinetrue) {#function-__logwrite__msg-newlinetrue}

Write one message to the log.

__Example:__

{% highlight python %}
# Write a single string of text
log.write(u'time = %s' % clock.time())
{% endhighlight %}

__Arguments:__

- `msg` -- A text message.
	- Type: str, unicode

__Keywords:__

- `newline` -- Indicates whether a newline should be written after the message.
	- Default: True
	- Type: bool

</div>

[log.write]: #log-write
[write]: #log-write

<div class="FunctionDoc YAMLDoc" id="log-write_vars" markdown="1">

## [function __log\.write\_vars__\(var\_list=None\)](#function-__logwrite_vars__var_listnone) {#function-__logwrite_vars__var_listnone}

Writes variables to the log.

__Example:__

{% highlight python %}
# Write all variables to the logfile
log.write_vars()
{% endhighlight %}

__Keywords:__

- `var_list` -- A list of variable names to write, or None to write all variables that exist in the experiment.
	- Default: None
	- Type: list, NoneType

</div>

[log.write_vars]: #log-write_vars
[write_vars]: #log-write_vars

</div>

